RMP Executive Summary

Accidental Release Prevention & Emergency Response Policies

RMax Inc.'s management, at both the plant and corporate level, is committed to the safety and health of its employees, contractors, and visitors, and to minimizing to the greatest extent practicable the potential for releases which may adversely affect the environment. This commitment is a critical element of the facility's RMP/PSM Plan. It will extend not only through the initial development of the plan, but will endeavor to incorporate the practices and procedures established by this plan into the facility's normal way of conducting day-to-day business. RMax has established a management system to oversee the development, implementation, and successful continuing implementation of its RMP/PSM Plan. The goals of this system are:

* Clarify the roles/responsibilities related to process safety issues at the facility;
* Avoid problems or conflicts among the various people responsible for implementing elements of the risk management plan;
* Avoid confusion and allow those responsible for implementation to work together as a team;
* Ensure that the program elements are integrated into an ongoing approach to identifying hazards and managing risks;
* Ensure effective communication about process changes;
* Provide full compliance to all regulatory requirements.

The overall implementation of the RMP/PSM Plan is the responsibility of the Plant Manager. Under this plan, it is his duty to ensure all elements are ultimately implemented as described. Although other employees will have key roles in the RMP/PSM Plan, the Plant Manager assumes this overall primary responsibility.

It is in the best interest of Rmax and it's employees to continually evaluate potential safety issues. Should any employee find any area or practice to be a potential safety hazard, a supervisor is informed. RMAX's policy is not to wait for someone

azing.  Upon arrival, a subcontractor who will perform "Hot Work" is signed in at the front receptionist office and supervised by RMax personnel continuously for the duration of his/her work. The "Hot Work Permit" details the required precautions checklist and monitoring required throughout the duration of the project.  In addition, the "Hot Work Permit" must be located at the perimeter of the defined work area until work is completed. These requirements apply not only to subcontractors but also to RMax employees who will be performing any type of welding, cutting, brazing, etc. 

Numerous safety systems have been installed at RMax in order to reduce the potential for a release of, or an employee exposure to, Blowing Agent. These systems include: the hydrocarbon injection system relief/recirculation system; the interlocked controls of the process; the ventilation system; the hydrocarbon sensor system; the manual E-stops at various locations, and the facility's grounding protection system. In accordance with the requirements of 40 CFR 68.73 and 29 CFR 1910.119(j), RMax has developed and implemented written procedures to maintain the on-going integrity of its hydrocarbon injection system. These procedures apply to the following types of process equipment:

* Pressure vessels and storage tanks;
* Piping systems (including piping components such as valves);
* Relief and vent systems and devices;
* Emergency shutdown systems;
* Controls (including monitoring devices and sensors, alarms, and interlocks);
* Pumps.

RMax's procedures for maintaining the integrity of its hydrocarbon injection system will include training of maintenance personnel, preventive maintenance inspection/testing, and a system to immediately correct any deficiencies noted. RMax's maintenance personnel are primarily responsible for maintaining the mechanical integrity of its hydrocarbon injection system. Maintenance personnel receive training that includes an overview of the process and its hazards. I

pment has been used in accordance with manufacturer's instructions, by requesting and receiving certifications/warranty statements to that effect from the designers/builders/suppliers of the process. In addition to the testing performed on individual system components by the manufacturer, and prior to the initial introduction of Blowing Agent into the process, certain parts of the hydrocarbon injection system will be tested as follows:

- Piping between unloading bulkhead and tank (including vapor return line): pneumatically tested at 100 psi;
- Bulk storage tank: pressure/leak tested with plant air at 100 psi;
- Piping from tank to Lewa pump enclosure: pneumatically tested at 100 psi;
- PLC Program and Main Control Panel: inspected/tested prior to shipment to RMax;
- Metering/injection system: leak and pressure tested prior to shipment to RMax; 
- System equipment from high pressure pumps to injection point: leak/pressure tested with water to 3500 psi for extended period of time once installation at RMax is completed;
- Control system: ability of system to track within the proper parameters established and verified once installation at RMax is completed;
- Drager monitoring/alarm system: sensor alarms tested to verify announcement of proper alarms and shutdown of proper equipment once installation at RMax is completed;
- Startup/Shutdown sequences: programmed and tested to be operational once installation at RMax is completed.

Documentation of the above described testing will be located in design information that has been supplied to RMax by each supplier and/or in the RMP/PSM Plan. RMax has performed a Pre-Startup Safety Review to assure that the hydrocarbon injection system has been installed in accordance with design specifications.

